## The Highway Selection Problem Nobody Mentions

When I first started driving this route regularly, I followed GPS directions without questioning the route selection logic. Big mistake. The mapping systems recommend different highways depending on current traffic conditions, but they don't account for the long-term patterns that affect reliability for scheduled transportation services.

The primary route takes US-36 north through Westminster and Broomfield, then connects to I-25 north before picking up US-34 west into Loveland. This appears optimal on paper because it uses major highways for most of the journey. The reality is more complicated because each highway segment has different peak traffic periods that don't align predictably.

US-36 experiences eastbound morning congestion from Boulder commuters heading to Denver, but westbound afternoon delays from Denver residents going home to Boulder and Louisville communities. This means the same highway has opposite traffic patterns depending on direction and time of day. Car services that don't account for this bidirectional complexity end up stuck in unexpected delays.

I-25 north from the US-36 junction to the US-34 exit creates its own timing challenges. The highway handles commuter traffic between Denver and Fort Collins, but it also carries tourist traffic to Estes Park and Rocky Mountain National Park. Because of its location along U.S. 34, at one of the principal access routes to Estes Park and Rocky Mountain National Park, Loveland receives significant seasonal traffic. During summer weekends, recreational traffic doubles normal volume between 9 AM and 2 PM.

The alternative route through Denver on I-76 to I-25 adds approximately 8 miles but can save 15-20 minutes during peak traffic periods. However, most car services avoid this route because the additional mileage affects their cost calculations, even when it provides faster service. This creates a disconnect between what customers want (reliable timing) and how services calculate pricing (distance-based).

